1
00:00:55,720 --> 00:00:58,140
I think there must be
something wrong with me, Linus.

2
00:00:58,300 --> 00:01:00,470
Christmas is coming, but I'm not happy.

3
00:01:00,640 --> 00:01:03,310
I don't feel the way l'm supposed to feel.

4
00:01:06,690 --> 00:01:09,400
I just don't understand Christmas,
I guess.

5
00:01:09,570 --> 00:01:12,690
I like getting presents
and sending Christmas cards...

6
00:01:12,860 --> 00:01:16,070
...and decorating trees and all that,
but I'm still not happy.

7
00:01:16,240 --> 00:01:18,490
I always end up feeling depressed.

8
00:01:18,660 --> 00:01:21,660
Charlie Brown,
you're the only person l know...

9
00:01:21,830 --> 00:01:26,000
...who can take a wonderful season
like Christmas and turn it into a problem.

10
00:01:26,170 --> 00:01:27,330
Maybe Lucy's right.

11
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:32,670
Of all the Charlie Browns in the world,
you're the Charlie Browniest.

12
00:02:28,890 --> 00:02:31,400
[ECHOES]
Hello in there.

13
00:02:32,060 --> 00:02:33,690
Rats.

14
00:02:33,860 --> 00:02:36,150
Nobody sent me a Christmas card today.

15
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:38,570
I almost wish
there weren't a holiday season.

16
00:02:38,740 --> 00:02:40,070
I know nobody likes me.

17
00:02:40,570 --> 00:02:43,410
Why do we have to have a holiday season
to emphasize it?

18
00:02:46,080 --> 00:02:49,660
Thanks for the Christmas card
you sent me, Violet.

19
00:02:49,830 --> 00:02:54,130
I didn't send you a Christmas card,
Charlie Brown.

20
00:02:55,050 --> 00:02:58,420
Don't you know sarcasm
when you hear it?

21
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:03,890
Pigpen,
you're the only person l know...

22
00:03:04,050 --> 00:03:06,390
...who can raise a cloud of dust
in a snowstorm.

23
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:08,560
[CHOMPlNG]

24
00:03:18,030 --> 00:03:20,320
Try to catch snowflakes
on your tongue.

25
00:03:21,570 --> 00:03:23,410
It's fun.

26
00:03:24,030 --> 00:03:26,330
Mm. Needs sugar.

27
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:31,870
It's too early.
I never eat December snowflakes.

28
00:03:32,040 --> 00:03:34,330
I always wait until January.

29
00:03:35,090 --> 00:03:37,340
They sure look ripe to me.

30
00:04:03,570 --> 00:04:06,530
You think you're so smart
with that blanket.

31
00:04:06,700 --> 00:04:09,040
What are you gonna do with it
when you grow up?

32
00:04:09,790 --> 00:04:12,290
Maybe I'll make it into a sport coat.

33
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:24,510
I think you have a customer.

34
00:04:32,180 --> 00:04:33,600
May I help you?

35
00:04:33,770 --> 00:04:36,190
-l'm in sad shape.
-Wait a minute.

36
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:38,810
Before you begin,
I must ask that you pay in advance.

37
00:04:38,980 --> 00:04:41,150
Five cents, please.

38
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:46,530
Boy, what a sound.

39
00:04:46,910 --> 00:04:51,700
How I love to hear that old money plink,
that beautiful sound of cold, hard cash.

40
00:04:51,870 --> 00:04:55,040
That beautiful, beautiful sound.
Nickels, nickels, nickels.

41
00:04:55,210 --> 00:04:58,330
That beautiful sound of plinking nickels.

42
00:04:58,920 --> 00:05:02,960
All right, now,
what seems to be your trouble?

43
00:05:03,130 --> 00:05:07,050
I feel depressed.
I know l should be happy, but I'm not.

44
00:05:07,220 --> 00:05:09,220
Well, as they say on TV...

45
00:05:09,390 --> 00:05:11,640
...the mere fact
that you realize you need help...

46
00:05:11,810 --> 00:05:14,060
...indicates that you are not too far gone.

47
00:05:14,230 --> 00:05:16,390
I think we'd better pinpoint your fears.

48
00:05:16,560 --> 00:05:19,520
If we can find out what you're afraid of,
we can label it.

49
00:05:19,690 --> 00:05:24,740
Are you afraid of responsibility?
If you are, then you have hypengyophobia.

50
00:05:25,240 --> 00:05:27,490
-l don't think that's quite it.
-How about cats?

51
00:05:27,660 --> 00:05:31,030
If you're afraid of cats,
you have ailurophasia.

52
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:33,080
Well, sort of, but l'm not sure.

53
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:37,750
Are you afraid of staircases?
If you are, then you have climacophobia.

54
00:05:37,920 --> 00:05:40,750
Maybe you have thalassophobia.
This is fear of the ocean.

55
00:05:41,170 --> 00:05:44,510
Or gephyrophobia,
which is the fear of crossing bridges.

56
00:05:44,670 --> 00:05:48,590
Or maybe you have pantophobia.
Do you think you have pantophobia?

57
00:05:48,760 --> 00:05:52,140
-What's pantophobia?
-The fear of everything.

58
00:05:52,310 --> 00:05:54,270
[SHOUTING]
That's it!

59
00:05:55,230 --> 00:05:59,150
Actually, Lucy, my trouble is Christmas.
I just don't understand it.

60
00:05:59,310 --> 00:06:02,110
Instead of feeling happy,
I feel sort of let down.

61
00:06:02,270 --> 00:06:03,610
You need involvement.

62
00:06:03,780 --> 00:06:06,610
You need to get involved
in some real Christmas project.

63
00:06:06,780 --> 00:06:09,610
How would you like to be the director
of our Christmas play?

64
00:06:09,780 --> 00:06:14,080
Me? You want me to be the director
of the Christmas play?

65
00:06:14,240 --> 00:06:18,080
Sure, Charlie Brown.
We need a director, you need involvement.

66
00:06:18,460 --> 00:06:22,540
We've got a shepherd, musicians,
animals, everyone you need.

67
00:06:22,710 --> 00:06:26,510
We've even got a Christmas queen.

68
00:06:26,670 --> 00:06:29,220
I don't know anything
about directing a Christmas play.

69
00:06:29,380 --> 00:06:33,100
Don't worry, l'll be there to help you.
I'll meet you at the auditorium.

70
00:06:33,260 --> 00:06:36,810
Incidentally, I know how you feel
about all this Christmas business...

71
00:06:36,980 --> 00:06:38,560
...getting depressed and all that.

72
00:06:38,730 --> 00:06:42,650
It happens to me every year.
I never get what l really want.

73
00:06:42,810 --> 00:06:45,440
I always get a lot of stupid toys
or a bicycle...

74
00:06:45,610 --> 00:06:48,030
...or clothes or something like that.

75
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:51,700
-What is it you want?
-Real estate.

76
00:07:06,050 --> 00:07:08,840
What's going on here?

77
00:07:09,010 --> 00:07:10,010
What's this?

78
00:07:10,180 --> 00:07:14,220
"Find the true meaning of Christmas.
Win money, money, money.

79
00:07:14,390 --> 00:07:20,520
Spectacular, super-colossal neighborhood
Christmas-lights-and-display contest."

80
00:07:20,690 --> 00:07:25,020
Lights-and-display contest? Oh, no.

81
00:07:26,110 --> 00:07:30,530
My own dog gone commercial.
I can't stand it. Oh....

82
00:07:32,570 --> 00:07:35,530
I've been looking for you, big brother.

83
00:07:35,700 --> 00:07:39,250
Will you please write a letter
to Santa Claus for me?

84
00:07:39,410 --> 00:07:41,040
Well, l don't have much time.

85
00:07:41,210 --> 00:07:45,040
I'm supposed to get down to the school
auditorium and direct a Christmas play.

86
00:07:45,210 --> 00:07:48,960
You write it,
and l'll tell you what l want to say.

87
00:07:49,130 --> 00:07:50,510
Okay, shoot.

88
00:07:50,670 --> 00:07:55,010
Dear Santa Claus, how have you been?
Did you have a nice summer?

89
00:07:55,970 --> 00:07:57,180
How is your wife?

90
00:07:57,350 --> 00:07:59,470
I have been extra good this year...

91
00:07:59,640 --> 00:08:02,600
...so l have a long list of presents
that I want.

92
00:08:02,770 --> 00:08:05,400
Oh, brother.

93
00:08:05,560 --> 00:08:10,070
Please note the size and color of each item
and send as many as possible.

94
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:14,110
If it seems too complicated,
make it easy on yourself:

95
00:08:14,280 --> 00:08:15,700
Just send money.

96
00:08:15,870 --> 00:08:20,410
-How about 1 0s and 20s?
-Tens and 20s? Oh....

97
00:08:20,580 --> 00:08:22,710
Even my baby sister.

98
00:08:22,870 --> 00:08:27,920
All I want is what I have coming to me.
All I want is my fair share.

99
00:08:29,380 --> 00:08:32,380
[UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

100
00:08:42,230 --> 00:08:44,310
All right, quiet, everybody.

101
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:47,610
Our director will be here any minute
and we'll start rehearsal.

102
00:08:47,770 --> 00:08:51,320
-Director? What director?
-Charlie Brown.

103
00:08:51,480 --> 00:08:57,160
-Oh, no, we're doomed.
-This will be the worst Christmas play ever.

104
00:08:57,320 --> 00:09:01,160
Here he comes.
Attention, everyone, here's our director.

105
00:09:01,370 --> 00:09:02,410
[APPLAUDlNG]

106
00:09:02,580 --> 00:09:04,500
Booooooo.

107
00:09:06,290 --> 00:09:09,210
Man's best friend.

108
00:09:10,460 --> 00:09:12,630
Well, it's real good seeing y'all here.

109
00:09:12,800 --> 00:09:15,340
As you know,
we are going to put on the Christmas play.

110
00:09:15,510 --> 00:09:18,260
Due to the shortage of time,
we'll get right down to work.

111
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:21,310
One of the first things
to insure a good performance...

112
00:09:21,470 --> 00:09:23,470
...is strict attention to the director.

113
00:09:23,640 --> 00:09:25,430
I'll keep my directions simple.

114
00:09:25,600 --> 00:09:29,650
If l point to the right,
it means focus attention stage right.

115
00:09:29,810 --> 00:09:32,270
If l make a slashing motion
across my throat...

116
00:09:32,440 --> 00:09:34,030
...it means cut the scene short.

117
00:09:34,190 --> 00:09:38,320
If l make a revolving motion with my hand,
it means pick up the tempo.

118
00:09:38,490 --> 00:09:42,160
If l spread my hands apart,
it means slow down.

119
00:09:42,330 --> 00:09:47,410
It's the spirit of the actors that counts,
the interest that they show in their director.

120
00:09:47,580 --> 00:09:51,290
Am l right? l said, am l right?

121
00:09:51,460 --> 00:09:54,460
[PLAYING VINCE GUARALDI'S
"LINUS & LUCY"]

122
00:10:22,830 --> 00:10:25,620
Stop the music! All right, now.

123
00:10:25,790 --> 00:10:29,040
We're going to do this play
and we're going to do it right.

124
00:10:29,460 --> 00:10:32,710
Lucy, get those costumes and scripts
and pass them out.

125
00:10:32,880 --> 00:10:36,590
Now, the script girl
will be handing out your parts.

126
00:10:36,760 --> 00:10:38,420
You're the innkeeper's wife.

127
00:10:38,590 --> 00:10:43,100
Do innkeepers' wives
have naturally curly hair?

128
00:10:43,850 --> 00:10:45,970
Pigpen, you're the innkeeper.

129
00:10:46,140 --> 00:10:51,350
In spite of my outward appearance,
I shall try to run a neat inn.

130
00:10:51,730 --> 00:10:54,610
Shermy, you're a shepherd.

131
00:10:55,360 --> 00:11:00,070
Every Christmas it's the same.
I always end up playing a shepherd.

132
00:11:00,860 --> 00:11:04,200
Snoopy, you'll have to be all the animals
in our play.

133
00:11:04,370 --> 00:11:06,490
-Can you be a sheep?
-Baa.

134
00:11:06,660 --> 00:11:08,790
-How about a cow?
-Moo.

135
00:11:09,580 --> 00:11:11,790
How about a penguin?

136
00:11:14,090 --> 00:11:17,420
-Yes, he's even a good penguin.
-Ooow!

137
00:11:19,920 --> 00:11:21,430
No, no, no.

138
00:11:21,590 --> 00:11:24,890
Listen, all of you.
You've got to take direction.

139
00:11:25,060 --> 00:11:27,010
[LUCY SPEAKlNG AND SNOOPY MOUTHlNG]
You've got to have discipline.

140
00:11:27,180 --> 00:11:31,600
You've gotta have respect
for your director.

141
00:11:32,060 --> 00:11:34,310
I ought to slug you.

142
00:11:34,480 --> 00:11:37,940
Ugh. I've been kissed by a dog.
I have dog germs.

143
00:11:38,110 --> 00:11:41,450
Get hot water,
get some disinfectant, get some iodine.

144
00:11:41,610 --> 00:11:43,200
-Waaah.
-Ah.

145
00:11:43,370 --> 00:11:47,160
All right, all right, script girl,
continue with the scripts.

146
00:11:49,160 --> 00:11:52,920
Linus, you've got to get rid
of that stupid blanket.

147
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:55,460
And here, memorize these lines.

148
00:11:55,630 --> 00:11:59,210
I can't memorize these lines.
This is ridiculous.

149
00:11:59,380 --> 00:12:02,340
Memorize it and be ready to recite
when your cue comes.

150
00:12:02,510 --> 00:12:05,140
I can't memorize something like this
so quickly.

151
00:12:05,300 --> 00:12:08,180
Why should I be put through such agony?

152
00:12:08,350 --> 00:12:11,680
Give me one good reason
why l should memorize this.

153
00:12:11,850 --> 00:12:17,820
I'll give you five good reasons:
One, two, three, four, five.

154
00:12:17,980 --> 00:12:19,320
Those are good reasons.

155
00:12:19,780 --> 00:12:22,030
Christmas is not only
getting too commercial...

156
00:12:22,200 --> 00:12:24,530
...it's getting too dangerous.

157
00:12:24,700 --> 00:12:26,820
And get rid of that stupid blanket.

158
00:12:26,990 --> 00:12:29,080
What's a Christmas shepherd
gonna look like...

159
00:12:29,240 --> 00:12:31,160
...holding a stupid blanket like that?

160
00:12:31,330 --> 00:12:33,160
Well, this is one Christmas shepherd...

161
00:12:33,330 --> 00:12:35,670
...who's going to keep his trusty blanket
with him.

162
00:12:35,830 --> 00:12:38,840
See? You wouldn't hit
an innocent shepherd, would you?

163
00:12:39,800 --> 00:12:43,760
Okay, Mr. Director, the cast is set.
Take over.

164
00:12:43,930 --> 00:12:47,720
All right, let's have it quiet.
Places, everybody.

165
00:12:47,890 --> 00:12:51,640
Schroeder, set the mood for first scene.

166
00:12:52,430 --> 00:12:55,440
[PLAYING VINCE GUARALDI'S
"LINUS & LUCY"]

167
00:12:56,980 --> 00:12:59,820
Cut, cut. No, no, no.

168
00:13:01,150 --> 00:13:03,990
Look, let's rehearse the scene at the inn.

169
00:13:04,150 --> 00:13:07,410
-Frieda, this is--
-We can't go on. There's too much dust.

170
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:11,080
It's taking the curl
out of my naturally curly hair.

171
00:13:11,240 --> 00:13:12,870
Don't think of it as dust.

172
00:13:13,040 --> 00:13:17,830
Think of it as maybe the soil
of some great past civilization.

173
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:22,710
Maybe the soil of ancient Babylon.
It staggers the imagination.

174
00:13:22,880 --> 00:13:26,430
He may be carrying soil
that was trod upon by Solomon.

175
00:13:26,590 --> 00:13:28,340
Or even Nebuchadnezzar.

176
00:13:28,510 --> 00:13:32,350
It sort of makes you wanna treat me
with more respect, doesn't it?

177
00:13:32,520 --> 00:13:35,850
You're an absolute mess.
Just look at yourself.

178
00:13:37,230 --> 00:13:40,360
On the contrary,
I didn't think l'd look that good.

179
00:13:40,520 --> 00:13:42,860
Sally, come here.

180
00:13:43,570 --> 00:13:47,450
-What do you want her for?
-She's gonna be your wife.

181
00:13:50,240 --> 00:13:52,410
Good grief.

182
00:13:52,580 --> 00:13:55,620
Isn't he the cutest thing?

183
00:13:56,960 --> 00:14:00,460
He has the nicest sense of humor.

184
00:14:01,540 --> 00:14:05,760
-Lunch break, lunch break.
-Lunch break?

185
00:14:11,760 --> 00:14:14,430
All right, now,
there's no time for foolishness.

186
00:14:14,600 --> 00:14:17,980
We've got to get on with our play.

187
00:14:18,140 --> 00:14:21,310
That's right. What about my part?

188
00:14:22,650 --> 00:14:25,440
What about the Christmas queen, hmm?

189
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:30,030
Are you going to let all this beauty
go to waste?

190
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:34,450
You do think I'm beautiful, don't you,
Charlie Brown?

191
00:14:34,620 --> 00:14:39,000
You didn't answer me right away.
You had to think about it first, didn't you?

192
00:14:39,170 --> 00:14:42,830
If you really had thought I was beautiful,
you would've spoken right up.

193
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:46,090
I know when l've been insulted.
I know when l've been insulted.

194
00:14:46,260 --> 00:14:48,340
Good grief.

195
00:14:49,720 --> 00:14:52,390
All right, let's take it from the top again.

196
00:14:52,550 --> 00:14:55,810
Places. Action.

197
00:14:55,970 --> 00:14:58,980
[PLAYING VINCE GUARALDI'S
"LINUS & LUCY"]

198
00:15:05,360 --> 00:15:08,740
Charlie Brown, isn't it a great play?

199
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:10,650
That does it.

200
00:15:10,820 --> 00:15:13,570
Now, look, if we're ever to get this play
off the ground...

201
00:15:13,740 --> 00:15:16,830
...we've gotta have some cooperation.

202
00:15:17,580 --> 00:15:20,960
What's the matter, Charlie Brown?
Don't you think it's great?

203
00:15:21,120 --> 00:15:24,750
-lt's all wrong.
-Look, Charlie, let's face it.

204
00:15:24,920 --> 00:15:27,630
We all know that Christmas
is a big commercial racket.

205
00:15:27,800 --> 00:15:30,220
It's run by a big Eastern syndicate,
you know.

206
00:15:30,630 --> 00:15:33,260
Well, this is one play
that's not gonna be commercial.

207
00:15:33,430 --> 00:15:36,350
-Look, Charlie Brown, what do you want?
-The proper mood.

208
00:15:36,510 --> 00:15:39,560
-We need a Christmas tree.
-Hey, perhaps a tree.

209
00:15:39,730 --> 00:15:43,020
A great big, shiny,
aluminum Christmas tree.

210
00:15:43,190 --> 00:15:47,690
That's it, Charlie Brown. You get the tree.
I'll handle this crowd.

211
00:15:47,860 --> 00:15:52,450
Okay. l'll take Linus with me.
The rest of you practice your lines.

212
00:15:52,610 --> 00:15:56,700
Get the biggest aluminum tree you can find,
Charlie Brown, maybe painted pink.

213
00:15:56,870 --> 00:16:01,330
Yeah, do something right for a change,
Charlie Brown.

214
00:16:04,880 --> 00:16:09,340
I don't know, Linus. I just don't know.

215
00:16:10,550 --> 00:16:14,510
Well, l guess we'd better concentrate
on finding a nice Christmas tree.

216
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:20,390
I suggest we try those searchlights,
Charlie Brown.

217
00:16:27,110 --> 00:16:28,690
[HOLLOW METAL ECHOlNG]

218
00:16:28,860 --> 00:16:32,070
This really brings Christmas close
to a person.

219
00:16:32,240 --> 00:16:34,860
Fantastic.

220
00:16:51,510 --> 00:16:54,880
LlNUS: Gee, do they still make
wooden Christmas trees?

221
00:16:55,050 --> 00:16:57,930
CHARLlE: This little green one here
seems to need a home.

222
00:16:58,100 --> 00:16:59,810
I don't know, Charlie Brown.

223
00:16:59,970 --> 00:17:04,230
Remember what Lucy said?
This doesn't seem to fit the modern spirit.

224
00:17:04,390 --> 00:17:05,440
I don't care.

225
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:08,560
We'll decorate it,
and it'll be just right for our play.

226
00:17:08,730 --> 00:17:11,400
Besides, l think it needs me.

227
00:17:18,620 --> 00:17:22,910
This is the music l've selected
for the Christmas play.

228
00:17:23,080 --> 00:17:26,580
[PLAYING BEETHOVEN'S "FÃœR ELISE"]

229
00:17:27,630 --> 00:17:29,840
What kind of Christmas music is that?

230
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:32,670
Beethoven Christmas music.

231
00:17:33,090 --> 00:17:35,340
What has Beethoven got to do
with Christmas?

232
00:17:35,510 --> 00:17:38,010
Everyone talks
about how great Beethoven was.

233
00:17:38,180 --> 00:17:40,430
Beethoven wasn't so great.

234
00:17:40,600 --> 00:17:43,970
What do you mean,
Beethoven wasn't so great?

235
